React.createElement("h1", null, "Hello")

Very hard to read.

Solution → JSX
JSX makes it look like HTML:

Much cleaner 
More readable 
Less syntax burden 


JSX (JavaScript XML) is a syntax extension for JavaScript that allows writing HTML-like code inside JavaScript.

JSX is NOT HTML
JSX is NOT understood by browsers
JSX must be converted to JavaScript

<h1>Hello</h1> ----->  React.createElement("h1", null, "Hello")
So JSX is syntactic sugar over React.createElement




Babel as a Transcompiler

Since browsers do NOT understand JSX, we need a converter.

What is Babel?
Babel is a JavaScript transcompiler that converts modern JS + JSX into browser-compatible JavaScript.


It converts:

JSX → React.createElement
ES6 → ES5
Optional chaining → safe JS


Why Not Use Babel CDN in Production?

Slow (compiles in browser)
Large file size
Not optimized

Production uses:
Vite
Webpack
esbuild


Functions Analogy for React Component:

function Greeting({ name }) {
  return <h1>Hello {name}</h1>;
}

<Greeting name="Aniket" />
<Greeting name="Rahul" />
<Greeting name="Priya" />

function Card({ title, children }) {
  return (
    <div className="card">
      <h2>{title}</h2>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}

<Card title="Profile">
  <p>User details here</p>
</Card>



JSX → Sugar syntax
Babel → Converts JSX to JS
Component → Function returning JSX
Props → Function arguments
Element → Object describing UI
Reusability → Components + Props





